[3] Antigua and Barbuda
Date: Fri 9 May 2014
Source: The Antigua Observer [edited]
http://www.antiguaobserver.com/disease-spreads/


The Ministry of Health says 3 more cases of chikungunya fever have been confirmed in Antigua & Barbuda by the Caribbean Public Health Agency (CARPHA). This brings the number of confirmed cases in the country to 4 as of yesterday [8 May 2014].

The chikungunya virus is transmitted to people by mosquitoes. The most common symptoms of chikungunya virus infection are fever and joint pain. Other symptoms may include headache, muscle pain, joint swelling, or rash.

The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) says there is no vaccine to prevent or medicine to treat chikungunya virus infection.

The Ministry of Health issued a release, which advised that "since the virus is new to Antigua, persons would have limited immunity to the disease, and since the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito -- the vector that transmits the disease [virus] -- is present here, the number of cases is expected to increase."

The statement added: "Persons are, therefore, asked to take measures to avoid mosquito bites and to be aware of the symptoms that may include a high fever of sudden onset, severe joint pain, and a rash."

