[5] Brazil imported
Date: Fri 9 May 2014
Source: O Rio Branco [in Portuguese, summ. & trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.oriobranco.net/component/content/article/29-destaque/37937-novo-virus-pior-do-que-a-dengue-ameaca-entrar-no-ap-pela-guiana.html


At the beginning of April [2014], the Secretariat of Health received an alert from the government of French Guiana about a new virus [chikungunya] that is more aggressive than that which causes dengue and has hit some victims in this French department.

[Arrival of] this new virus is imminent in various areas of Brazil, mainly in the states bordering the Caribbean where the virus's [geographic range] is expanding. This reality hit Amapa and Roraima states, which are now receiving redoubled attention by the Ministry of Health due to cases found in the Guiana Plateau and Venezuela [The accuracy of cases in Venezuela is questioned, since no cases have been reported there thus far. Mod.TY].

Up until now, the confirmed cases in Brazil were brought in by people who were outside the country. Because of this, the Ministry of Health is extremely concerned about the entry of this new virus from the countries on the northern border of Brazil.

This concern has increased now with the coming of the FIFA World Cup games, when the country will receive a large number of tourists coming from a wide variety of points around the world who could bring new cases of the disease.

--
Communicated by:
Roland Hubner
Superior Health Council
Brussels
Belgium
<roland.hubner@sante.belgique.be>

[Concern about the risk of introduction of chikungunya virus into Brazil given the upcoming influx of travelers for the FIFA World Cup is serious. The populations of vector mosquitoes in Brazil are adequate to permit ongoing transmission of the virus. Intensification of surveillance by public health authorities in the states bordering French Guiana is prudent. With the arrival of tens of thousand of individuals in various cities in Brazil for the World Cup games, surveillance will become a very major challenge.

Maps of Brazil can be seen at http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/brazil.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2467601,39007. - Mod.TY]

